<TITLE> Southern support buoys BJP </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 NEW DELHI, Mon May 11, (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - The following is a snapshot of recent developments in India's general election campaign. Days before the result of the general election, the main opposition Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP)-led alliance (NDA) has gained in strength with a key southern Indian party joining it. The Telangana Rashtra Samithi was earlier a partner of the "Third Front", an alliance of smaller parties spearheaded by the communists (all newspapers). The BJP, which has trailed the ruling Congress in most opinion polls, has also been buoyed by the reaffirmation of support by the Janata Dal (United) chief Nitish Kumar. Kumar, a long-time NDA ally whom the Congress had been wooing, was seen as non-committal until Sunday when he attended a full NDA meeting chaired by the alliance's prime ministerial candidate Lal Krishna Advani. The main communist party has said the government had underestimated the impact of the global financial crisis on India. "I think that for a pretty long time we'll be faced with serious problems in our economy," communist party of India (Marxist) chief Prakash Karat said. He said the country's economic growth in 2009-10 would be "lower" than 6-6.5 percent predicted by the government (The Hi
